nd":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Coughton, Warwickshire, , England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hatton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatten","meanings":["English: variant of   Hatton  . This surname is also common among African Americans.","North German: habitational name from the name of an area of marshland between Oldenburg and Bremen."]},{"name":"Hattan","meanings":["English and Scottish (Argyll): variant of   Hatton  ."]},{"name":"Aton","meanings":["variant of   Hatton  , with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>).","English:"]},{"name":"Heath","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) heath’ (Middle English <i>he(a)th</i>, Old English <i>hǣth</i>) or else a habitational name from any of numerous places called with this word. The same word also denoted heather, the characteristic plant of heathland areas. This surname has also been established in Dublin, Ireland, since the late 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma de Hatton was born about 1230, in Hatton, Cheshire, England, her father, William Hatton, was 31 and her mother, Agnes de Dutton, was 23. She married John I de Holt in 1254. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1294, in Warwick, Warwickshire, England, at the age of 65."},"et":{"about 1230–1294":"umbes 1230–1294","1228–1260":"1228–1260","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1225–1297":"1225–1297","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1209–Female":"1209–Surnud","1297":"1297","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","about 1228":"umbes 1228","1255":"1255","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","1209":"1209","about 1230":"umbes 1230","1317":"1317","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Coughton, Warwickshire, , England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1230–1294":"noin 1230–1294","1228–1260":"1228–1260","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1240–Male":